### Retrieve Request Headers and Cookies in Next.js App Directory Server Components

Source: https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/02-guides/migrating/app-router-migration.mdx

Illustrates how to retrieve request headers and cookies using the `headers()` and `cookies()` functions in the Next.js `app` directory. These Web API-based functions are typically used within Server Components to access read-only request-specific data.

```tsx
// `app` directory
import { cookies, headers } from 'next/headers'

async function getData() {
  const authHeader = (await headers()).get('authorization')

  return '...'
}

export default async function Page() {
  // You can use `cookies` or `headers` inside Server Components
  // directly or in your data fetching function
  const theme = (await cookies()).get('theme')
  const data = await getData()
  return '...'
}
```

```jsx
// `app` directory
import { cookies, headers } from 'next/headers'

async function getData() {
  const authHeader = (await headers()).get('authorization')

  return '...'
}

export default async function Page() {
  // You can use `cookies` or `headers` inside Server Components
  // directly or in your data fetching function
  const theme = (await cookies()).get('theme')
  const data = await getData()
  return '...'
}
```

