### GET /dashboard - Async Request APIs in Page Components

Source: https://context7.com/vercel/next.js/llms.txt

Demonstrates using async request APIs (cookies and headers) within a Next.js page component. This example shows how to access request cookies and headers in server components with the new async/await pattern introduced in Next.js 16, enabling better security and performance.

```APIDOC
## GET /dashboard

### Description
Server Component page that demonstrates accessing cookies and headers using the new async request APIs in Next.js 16. This pattern allows server components to safely access request-specific data like authentication tokens and user agent information while preventing accidental data leakage during prerendering.

### Method
GET

### Endpoint
/dashboard

### Request Headers
- **user-agent** (string) - Optional - Browser/client user agent string
- **Cookie** (string) - Optional - Contains auth-token and other cookies

### Response
HTML page displaying dashboard content with user agent and token information.

### Response Example
```html
<div>
  <h1>Dashboard</h1>
  <p>User Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64)...</p>
  <p>Token: eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...</p>
</div>
```

### Implementation Details
**File**: app/dashboard/page.tsx

**Key Features**:
- Component is async to support await for request APIs
- cookies() returns a CookieStore object after await
- headers() returns a Headers object after await
- Individual values retrieved using .get(name) method
- Token optional chaining (?.) safely accesses cookie value
- Automatically marks route as dynamic, disabling static prerendering

**Example Code**:
```typescript
import { cookies, headers } from 'next/headers';

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  // Async cookies API - requires await
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const token = cookieStore.get('auth-token');

  // Async headers API - requires await
  const headersList = await headers();
  const userAgent = headersList.get('user-agent');

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>
      <p>User Agent: {userAgent}</p>
      <p>Token: {token?.value}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Security Implications
- Async request APIs prevent data leakage during static prerendering
- Routes using these APIs are automatically treated as dynamic
- Request-specific data is only accessed when needed at request time
- Safer than synchronous alternatives that could accidentally capture data during build
```
